In general, for finding the amount of sensitivity of a reaction to temperature change, the quantity of dk/dT is a good choice. Rewriting Eq. (6) as Eq. (11),
11dkdT=kEaTRT2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \frac{dk}{dT}=\frac{kE_a(T)}{RT^2} $$\end{document}

it is obvious that both k and Ea appear as effective factors but usually, it is the quantity of dlnk/dT that is used in this regard. The point is that dlnk = dk/k is, in fact, the limit of Δk/k when ΔT → 0 and the fraction of Δk/k is a more suitable quantity for investigation of sensitivity compared to Δk. Therefore, Eq. (6) is more appropriate compared to Eq. (11) for evaluation of sensitivity to temperature. Rearranging Eq. (6) as Eq. (12),
12dlnkdT=EaTRT2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
